I'm doing my gratitude journal.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:50.040 align:middle line:84%
And I'm also listing
also the things

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:51.203 align:middle line:90%
that I want to do that day.

00:07:51.203 --> 00:07:53.620 align:middle line:84%
I do three things personally,
three things professionally.

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:55.320 align:middle line:90%
Those are my wins for the day.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.300 align:middle line:84%
And notice, I don't
even check my email

00:07:57.300 --> 00:07:59.400 align:middle line:84%
because one of the worst
habits people could have,

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:01.380 align:middle line:84%
if they want to be an
elite mental performer

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:03.338 align:middle line:84%
and they want to reach
their fullest potential,

00:08:03.338 --> 00:08:05.550 align:middle line:84%
do not touch your phone
the first hour of the day.

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:07.140 align:middle line:90%
And people-- and I'll say this.

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:08.220 align:middle line:90%
And a lot of people--

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:11.400 align:middle line:84%
because we're all addicted
to our digital devices--

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:13.060 align:middle line:90%
is because for two reasons.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:15.667 align:middle line:84%
It rewires your brain,
number one, for distraction.

00:08:15.667 --> 00:08:17.500 align:middle line:84%
When you wake up first
thing in the morning,

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:20.140 align:middle line:84%
you're in this brainwave
state called alpha/theta.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:22.890 align:middle line:84%
Alpha/theta states are the
states of relaxed awareness.

00:08:22.890 --> 00:08:25.290 align:middle line:90%
You're extremely impressionable.

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:28.170 align:middle line:84%
And when you're going on your
smart devices, and every time

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:30.330 align:middle line:84%
you get a like, or a
share, or a comment,

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:32.970 align:middle line:84%
or you're watching another
cat video, whatever, you're

00:08:32.970 --> 00:08:34.659 align:middle line:90%
getting this flood of dopamine.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:37.080 align:middle line:84%
But it's training you
to be more distracted.

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:39.120 align:middle line:84%
And we know this because
we live in a world

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:42.000 align:middle line:84%
full of distractions, app
notifications, social media

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:43.500 align:middle line:90%
alerts, Instagram.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.410 align:middle line:84%
And this is an app that we're
opening up 150, 200 times

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:48.600 align:middle line:84%
a day, highly addictive,
highly obituary.

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:51.750 align:middle line:84%
Dr. BJ Fogg, who
runs the Influence

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:54.300 align:middle line:84%
Lab in Stanford University,
one of his students

00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.550 align:middle line:90%
actually created Instagram.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:09:00.370 align:middle line:84%
But his expertise is in this
area of habit, habit creation

00:09:00.370 --> 00:09:01.170 align:middle line:90%
if you will.

00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:05.460 align:middle line:84%
He has this formula called
B MAT, B equals MAT.

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:07.470 align:middle line:84%
If you want to change
your habit, it starts--

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:09.145 align:middle line:84%
the behavior is
the habit itself.

00:09:09.145 --> 00:09:10.770 align:middle line:84%
Now in order to be
able to change that,

00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:12.660 align:middle line:84%
what creates a
habit or a behavior,

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:15.870 align:middle line:84%
is M-A-T. M is
motivation because you

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:18.910 align:middle line:84%
can't change a habit unless
you're motivated to do so.

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:23.100 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, if you want to
make exercise a habit, eating

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:25.940 align:middle line:84%
right a habit, journaling
or meditating a habit,

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:27.690 align:middle line:84%
you need to check in
with your motivation.

00:09:27.690 --> 00:09:30.210 align:middle line:84%
On a scale of 0 to
10, where are you

00:09:30.210 --> 00:09:31.860 align:middle line:84%
in your level of
motivation, your drive

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:34.410 align:middle line:84%
to be able to do that,
that activity if you will?

00:09:34.410 --> 00:09:37.120 align:middle line:84%
And the good thing about this
is if it's a 5, ask yourself,

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:40.830 align:middle line:84%
well, what do I need to do in
my mind to make it a 6 or a 7?

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:42.872 align:middle line:84%
And you could play these
little brain hack games,

00:09:42.872 --> 00:09:44.247 align:middle line:84%
to be able to
level up, like it's

00:09:44.247 --> 00:09:45.750 align:middle line:90%
a video game inside your mind.

00:09:45.750 --> 00:09:50.030 align:middle line:84%
The A in this formula
stands for ability, ability.

00:09:50.030 --> 00:09:51.690 align:middle line:84%
And you have
training in that area

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:53.297 align:middle line:90%
to be able to do that behavior.

00:09:53.297 --> 00:09:55.130 align:middle line:84%
So going back to, so
let's say your behavior

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:57.130 align:middle line:84%
is you want to be able
to read every single day.

00:09:57.130 --> 00:09:58.740 align:middle line:90%
Do you have the ability to read?

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:00.180 align:middle line:84%
Do you have
opportunities to read?

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:03.290 align:middle line:84%
And finally, the T-- this is
the big one in the formula--

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:06.530 align:middle line:84%
the T and B equals M-A-T.
When creating new habits,

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:08.450 align:middle line:90%
it stands for trigger.

00:10:08.450 --> 00:10:11.360 align:middle line:84%
And triggers are important to
me in my work as a memory expert

00:10:11.360 --> 00:10:13.860 align:middle line:84%
because everything
serves as a reminder.

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:15.810 align:middle line:84%
You can forget something
during the day.

00:10:15.810 --> 00:10:16.790 align:middle line:84%
You're like, what
was that actor's name

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:17.897 align:middle line:90%
or what did I need to do?

00:10:17.897 --> 00:10:19.480 align:middle line:84%
And later on, you're
driving your car.

00:10:19.480 --> 00:10:20.647 align:middle line:90%
All of sudden, what happens?

00:10:20.647 --> 00:10:21.890 align:middle line:90%
It just pops in your mind.

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:23.595 align:middle line:84%
Usually there's an
unconscious trigger.

00:10:23.595 --> 00:10:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Maybe a song that
goes off or something

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:27.440 align:middle line:84%
you see on the side road, that
unconsciously reminded you

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.690 align:middle line:84%
of the thing that you know
that's inside of your mind,

00:10:29.690 --> 00:10:31.232 align:middle line:84%
that you needed to
be able to recall.

00:10:31.232 --> 00:10:32.780 align:middle line:84%
But the trigger is
basically saying,

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:34.790 align:middle line:84%
what prompts you
to do that habit?

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:38.740 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, I don't
like digital devices so much.

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:40.490 align:middle line:84%
They're convenient,
but they also cripple.

00:10:40.490 --> 00:10:42.290 align:middle line:84%
We have this thing
called digital dementia,

00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:45.030 align:middle line:84%
where we're outsourcing our
brains to our smart devices.

00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:47.580 align:middle line:84%
Think about how many phone
numbers you knew growing up.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:48.380 align:middle line:90%
What?

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:49.340 align:middle line:90%
All of them, right.

00:10:49.340 --> 00:10:52.885 align:middle line:84%
How many phone numbers do you
know right now, one, maybe two.

00:10:52.885 --> 00:10:54.260 align:middle line:84%
And the challenge
is that I don't

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.310 align:middle line:84%
want to memorize hundreds
of phone numbers.

00:10:56.310 --> 00:10:58.520 align:middle line:84%
But we've lost the ability
just to memorize one.

00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:00.530 align:middle line:84%
They call it digital
dementia, meaning

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:02.840 align:middle line:84%
that we're using our smart
devices so much to keep

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:05.570 align:middle line:84%
our to-dos, our schedules,
our grocery list,

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:08.210 align:middle line:84%
do simple math for us,
remember all the phone numbers.

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:10.100 align:middle line:84%
So our brain's lost
the ability to be

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:11.720 align:middle line:90%
able to do those tasks ourself.

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:13.490 align:middle line:90%
It's just like GPS.

00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:16.880 align:middle line:84%
I was talking to Dr. Daniel
Amen, the famous brain doctor.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:19.880 align:middle line:84%
He says Jim, with GPS, we're
not getting early detection

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:22.130 align:middle line:84%
of dementia because
if you're relying

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:24.837 align:middle line:84%
on a piece of technology to
tell you where and when to turn,

00:11:24.837 --> 00:11:27.170 align:middle line:84%
you're not realizing when you
would have a memory lapse.

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:29.295 align:middle line:84%
And you're not going to
doctors to get checked out.

00:11:29.295 --> 00:11:31.670 align:middle line:84%
I think there are
three major challenges

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:34.370 align:middle line:84%
that the world's never faced
before in this digital age.

00:11:34.370 --> 00:11:36.470 align:middle line:84%
Number one's, digital
overload, too much

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:37.730 align:middle line:90%
information, too little time.

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:40.427 align:middle line:84%
The amount of information is
doubling at dizzying speeds.

00:11:40.427 --> 00:11:43.010 align:middle line:84%
The chairman of Google says that
the amount information that's

00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:44.990 align:middle line:84%
been created from
the dawn of humanity

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:47.870 align:middle line:84%
to the year 2003, which is
only about a decade and a half

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:50.960 align:middle line:84%
ago, that amount of information
now is created every two

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:51.800 align:middle line:90%
days online.

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:53.490 align:middle line:84%
I mean, think about
all the podcasts,

00:11:53.490 --> 00:11:55.700 align:middle line:84%
and all the blog posts,
and all the YouTube videos,

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:57.950 align:middle line:84%
and all the books, everything,
so much information.

00:11:57.950 --> 00:11:59.750 align:middle line:84%
So it's doubling
at dizzying speeds.

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:02.720 align:middle line:84%
But how we learn it,
has that changed?

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:05.240 align:middle line:84%
How we learn it, how we
read it, how we recall it,

00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:06.510 align:middle line:90%
has that changed, not at all.

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:09.170 align:middle line:84%
So that growing gap creates
a big health concern

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:11.900 align:middle line:84%
called information
anxiety, higher blood

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:15.800 align:middle line:84%
pressure, compression of leisure
time, more sleeplessness.

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:18.590 align:middle line:84%
Even if people have some free
time and something frees up

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:20.238 align:middle line:84%
in their life, a
meeting gets canceled,

00:12:20.238 --> 00:12:22.280 align:middle line:84%
they can't even enjoy
because their mind is still

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:24.620 align:middle line:84%
multitasking and
thinking of other things

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:26.203 align:middle line:90%
because we're wired to be busy.

00:12:26.203 --> 00:12:27.620 align:middle line:84%
Because people,
all the time, they

00:12:27.620 --> 00:12:31.110 align:middle line:84%
say-- you're used to saying,
I'm so busy, and how's today?

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:32.150 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I'm just so busy.

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:34.130 align:middle line:84%
And they're using that
as a badge of honor,

00:12:34.130 --> 00:12:35.600 align:middle line:90%
meaning it's an identity.

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:36.740 align:middle line:84%
Because here's the
unconscious message

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:37.760 align:middle line:90%
you're sending to somebody.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.343 align:middle line:84%
When you're saying
you're busy, you're

00:12:39.343 --> 00:12:40.580 align:middle line:90%
getting secondary gain and.

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:42.350 align:middle line:84%
That's secondary
gain is sympathy

00:12:42.350 --> 00:12:44.930 align:middle line:84%
or it's a feeling
of your significant.

00:12:44.930 --> 00:12:47.360 align:middle line:84%
Because you're so busy,
you must be important.

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:48.800 align:middle line:90%
And it's fulfilling these needs.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:50.900 align:middle line:84%
And so we are always
wanting to be busy,

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:51.920 align:middle line:90%
if that's your identity.

00:12:51.920 --> 00:12:55.130 align:middle line:84%
But here's the disservice
you give yourself, is this.

00:12:55.130 --> 00:12:57.290 align:middle line:84%
If you're always
identifying with being busy,

00:12:57.290 --> 00:12:59.780 align:middle line:84%
you are going to organize
your life to always be busy.

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:01.792 align:middle line:84%
And you wonder why you
don't have peace of mind.

00:13:01.792 --> 00:13:03.500 align:middle line:84%
You wonder why you
don't have a calmness.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:05.900 align:middle line:84%
Because I really think
that's the real currency,

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:08.450 align:middle line:84%
is your attention,
is your presence,

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:11.720 align:middle line:84%
is your confidence, and
a level of calmness,

00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:15.350 align:middle line:84%
in an age of, like, storms,
with digital distractions.

00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:17.810 align:middle line:84%
So number one, digital overload
creates the information

00:13:17.810 --> 00:13:18.610 align:middle line:90%
anxiety.

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:21.300 align:middle line:84%
That's why learning how to
learn faster is so important.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:24.640 align:middle line:84%
The other digital concern I
have is digital distraction.

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:26.780 align:middle line:84%
This idea, like nobody
can concentrate.

00:13:26.780 --> 00:13:29.090 align:middle line:84%
They say that human beings
now have less attention span

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:30.427 align:middle line:90%
than a goldfish.

00:13:30.427 --> 00:13:32.510 align:middle line:84%
And it's a big challenge
because how are you going

00:13:32.510 --> 00:13:33.680 align:middle line:90%
to build a quality of life?

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:34.610 align:middle line:84%
How are you going
to get things that

00:13:34.610 --> 00:13:36.650 align:middle line:84%
are most important
done if you can't even

00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:38.478 align:middle line:84%
focus on the thing
that's in front of you?

00:13:38.478 --> 00:13:40.520 align:middle line:84%
How many of us read a page
in a book, get to end,

00:13:40.520 --> 00:13:41.930 align:middle line:90%
just forgot what we just read?

00:13:41.930 --> 00:13:43.430 align:middle line:84%
How many people are
meeting somebody

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:44.870 align:middle line:84%
for the first time
and they don't

00:13:44.870 --> 00:13:46.940 align:middle line:84%
remember a name, not because
they don't have a great memory.

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:48.650 align:middle line:84%
It's because they're
looking over their shoulder

00:13:48.650 --> 00:13:51.110 align:middle line:84%
to see who else is important,
because they're not present.

00:13:51.110 --> 00:13:53.360 align:middle line:84%
How many people here, they're
not even looking around.

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:54.820 align:middle line:84%
Even if they're
looking at you, they're

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:56.960 align:middle line:84%
not really there because
they're talking to themselves.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:13:57.877 align:middle line:90%
They're not listening.

00:13:57.877 --> 00:14:00.078 align:middle line:84%
They're waiting for
their turn to speak

00:14:00.078 --> 00:14:02.370 align:middle line:84%
or they're thinking about
how they're going to respond.

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:03.890 align:middle line:84%
And one of my very
favorite books

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:06.500 align:middle line:84%
is by Dr. Stephen
Covey, "The 7 Habits

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:07.787 align:middle line:90%
of Highly Effective People."

00:14:07.787 --> 00:14:08.870 align:middle line:90%
And these are the habits--

00:14:08.870 --> 00:14:10.578 align:middle line:84%
we're going back to
habits and routines--

00:14:10.578 --> 00:14:11.870 align:middle line:90%
of the most effective people.

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:14.670 align:middle line:84%
One of them says, seek
first to understand,

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:16.260 align:middle line:90%
then to be understood.

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.470 align:middle line:84%
Seek first to understand,
then to be understood.

00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:20.080 align:middle line:84%
Like, for example,
remembering names,

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:21.710 align:middle line:84%
that's one the biggest
challenges, memory challenges,

00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:22.670 align:middle line:90%
people have.

00:14:22.670 --> 00:14:25.040 align:middle line:84%
And really, it's
not your retention.

00:14:25.040 --> 00:14:26.960 align:middle line:90%
It's your attention.

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:28.220 align:middle line:90%
It's your observation.

00:14:28.220 --> 00:14:30.470 align:middle line:84%
And when we're talking about,
like, even just boosting

00:14:30.470 --> 00:14:33.080 align:middle line:84%
our memory, we're talking about
being motivated, going back

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:33.980 align:middle line:90%
to motivation.

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:35.780 align:middle line:84%
Ask yourself, why do you
want to remember this?

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:37.670 align:middle line:84%
Why do I want to remember
this person's name?

00:14:37.670 --> 00:14:40.910 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's to make a
connection, make a new friend,

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:42.817 align:middle line:84%
or create a business
relationship.

00:14:42.817 --> 00:14:44.900 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's to practice
these techniques I learned.

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:47.525 align:middle line:84%
Because here's the thing, if you
can't come up with one reason,

00:14:47.525 --> 00:14:48.740 align:middle line:90%
you won't remember things.

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:53.000 align:middle line:84%
Because reasons reap results,
reasons reap results.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.680 align:middle line:84%
I think there's a
success formula.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:55.580 align:middle line:90%
I call it H-cubed.

00:14:55.580 --> 00:14:58.670 align:middle line:84%
It goes from your head, to
your heart, to your hands.

00:14:58.670 --> 00:15:00.440 align:middle line:84%
So we could visualize
things all day.

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:01.820 align:middle line:90%
We could set goals all day.

00:15:01.820 --> 00:15:04.220 align:middle line:84%
We could have our
dreams and our mind.

00:15:04.220 --> 00:15:06.890 align:middle line:84%
But if we're not acting with
our hands, something's going on.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:08.270 align:middle line:90%
Something is missing.

00:15:08.270 --> 00:15:11.210 align:middle line:84%
Because we're self-sabotaging
or we're procrastinating.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:13.760 align:middle line:84%
Why are we acting with our
hands when it's in our head?

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:16.710 align:middle line:84%
Usually what's missing is a
second H, which is the heart.

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:20.210 align:middle line:84%
The heart is a symbol of
emotion, the energy of motion.

00:15:20.210 --> 00:15:23.720 align:middle line:84%
Because you can't steer
a car that has no fuel.

00:15:23.720 --> 00:15:24.890 align:middle line:90%
So where's the fuel?

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:26.120 align:middle line:90%
You want to start with why.

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:27.490 align:middle line:90%
And so we go back to motivation.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:29.930 align:middle line:84%
Because here's the thing, a
lot of people know what to do.

00:15:29.930 --> 00:15:32.930 align:middle line:84%
